<font color="#FF0000">ALONG THE ROAD TO VIETNAM</font><br>
<tt>Tue Nov 12  6:55:09 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
   Great site you have here. As I read the comments two thoughts were came to me. 25 years and politics of the era and who practiced them. I joined the navy in July, 1968 40 days after graduating high school. Boot camp and service school lasted until April, 1969. I then was sent to Subic Bay, Philippines Is. for 18 months then onto the U.S.S. Oriskany (CVA-34) for a cruise to Vietnam. My job was to load the weapons onto A-7 Corsairs to bomb targets while we were there. <br><br>
   My thoughts came from that period earlier in 1969. After I had arrived in Subic, I got a letter from my Mother's mother. Grandma had opened the letter by saying how hard it was to believe that 25 years after she had written to her son on a ship off these same islands she was writting to her grandson on the islands. My uncle had enlisted at 18 and was  on board the U.S.S. Nashville (CL-47). This was the ship that MacArthur rode on to return to the Philippines. Meanwhile, 25 years later; grandson is loading bombs onto carriers and ammo ships to be used in-country. At least I didn't have to worry about kamikaze attacks like he did.   <br><br>
  On politics, the story is a little different. We had to stand roving fire watches for 4 hours at a time. We would report to a petty officer (E-4 to E-6) assigned for the night. Well if we weren't roving at the time, we'd be talking. <br><br>
   Well, one night I had this yeoman 3rd class (E-4 clerk) and he spent the time telling me about how great his life was. He had just become a born-again christian and how glad he was that god had put him there on a shore station for the rest of his enlistment. He said &quot; I'm glad I won't have to go on a ship because I could not stand to be on one of those  things&quot;. I was thinking to myself- why did you join the navy?? You should have gone into the Air Force.&quot; But whatever, at the time it didn't matter to me, I was looking forward to a little travel (or trying to). And judging by his own statements, I don't think he would have lasted too long anyway. <br><br>
   A couple of weeks later it came time to fill out our 'dream sheets' (station preferences- like it really mattered  but they did ask at least). And the born again christian was filling them out for us. Well, I didn't think they would send any of us to a PBR sqaudron or anywhere in Vietnam but hey why not try. Then I could honestly say I tried to get there no matter where I would be sent. But I was also a little shy and wasn't about to make a big deal of it. So I leaned over so only the clerk would hear me and said &quot; go ahead and put down Vietnam for the first choice&quot;. He looked up at me and screamed &quot;FISH&quot; so loud I almost fell over backward into the guy behind me. Now, I did restrain form hitting him, but since then I wonder what would have happended had I. It may have made an interesting Mast (known in the army as Article 15). But I kept cool then.<br>
   But you know, it's funny how many times I ran across like minded (to the clerk) people for the next few years. While Clinton and most of the college students were pestering the government; it was the christians against the war that walked thru Travis A.F.B. in Ca. passing out literature trying to convince us to desert. While students were taking over the admin building on campus's to get TV time, the self-acclaimed  followers of christ were trying to stop the 45,000 ton ship I was on with balloons filled with paint. Of course it didn't work; but who said these people had any brains or sympathy for the seaman who had to clean their mess up. <br><br>
   My point is that from those I would least expect it from was derision. College students were one thing; but these folks should all be grateful to us for taking their place. It is no wonder so many people feel ashamed of their actions in that era. And are trying to forget or (like some in congress) try to rewrite history to cover themselves.       
